# Security Best Practices

## Input Validation
- Validate all request DTOs with FluentValidation.
- Use length limits, regex allowlists, and numeric bounds.
- Keep all filtering, sorting, and paging in SQL (EF Core). Never build SQL strings.

## Secret Management
- Store secrets in Azure Key Vault only.
- Use managed identity in production.
- Never commit `appsettings.*.json`, `.env`, or credential files.

## Transport & Headers
- Enforce HTTPS and HSTS in production.
- Apply security headers: `X-Content-Type-Options`, `X-Frame-Options`, `Referrer-Policy`, `Permissions-Policy`, `Content-Security-Policy`.

## Tenant Isolation
- Enforce tenant filters in DbContext and verify tenant ownership in handlers.
- Never bypass tenant filters unless explicitly required and audited.

## Logging & Auditing
- Log authentication attempts, permission failures, and security-relevant events.
- Do not log secrets, tokens, or sensitive PII.

## Frontend Safety
- Avoid raw `innerHTML` unless sanitized.
- Use Angular sanitization APIs for any dynamic HTML.
- Prefer safe bindings and strict template typing.

## Dependency Hygiene
- Keep dependencies up to date.
- Audit for known vulnerabilities before releases.

## Security Checklist
- [ ] All secrets in Key Vault
- [ ] HTTPS + HSTS enforced
- [ ] Strong JWT keys and short lifetimes
- [ ] Rate limiting on auth endpoints
- [ ] Input validation on all endpoints
- [ ] Tenant isolation enforced
- [ ] Security headers enabled
- [ ] Sensitive data excluded from logs
